Stablecoins

The Stablecoin Leapfrog: How Emerging Markets are Bypassing Traditional Banking

Andrew Dyer

Nov 29, 2024 ⋅  15 min read

Key Insights

  • Emerging markets are rapidly adopting stablecoins to bypass traditional banking systems, driven by user-friendly applications and limited banking infrastructure.
  • Sub-Saharan Africa, Latin America, and Eastern Europe are experiencing the highest increases in crypto activity, significantly enhancing financial inclusion and reducing transaction costs.
  • Tron's strategic partnership with Binance and its low-fee, high-speed network have established it as a dominant platform for USDT transfers in emerging markets.
  • Crypto platforms like Bitso, Yellow Card, and Kuna are crucial in facilitating stablecoin transfers, international remittances, and value storage across major EMs.

Just as Emerging Markets (EM) once skipped desktop computers and moved directly to mobile devices, they are now poised to bypass traditional banking and payment systems in favor of stablecoins. While mobile leapfrogging was driven by affordable smartphones and expensive broadband infrastructure, stablecoin adoption will be fueled by easy-to-use apps and limited banking infrastructure. By embracing crypto infrastructure, regions like Africa, Latin America, and Eastern Europe can enhance financial inclusion, streamline cross-border payments, and significantly reduce costs.

In this report, we will explore evidence of retail stablecoin usage onchain, the close connections between this usage and centralized finance (CeFi), the companies driving the stablecoin movement, and who will benefit most from continued adoption.

A Quick Primer on Traditional EM Banking and Payments

According to Chainalysis’ 2024 report, Sub-Saharan Africa (SSA), Latin America, and Eastern Europe had the biggest increases in crypto activity year over year, so we will focus on these regions.

Sub-Saharan Africa

SSA has one of the lowest rates of formal financial account ownership globally. Around 49% of Sub-Saharan Africans own a bank account, whereas in developed countries this metric typically ranges from 93-99%. However, SSA is extremely diverse, and these numbers can be really low for a country like Mali, or close to developed markets’ levels in a country like South Africa. While account ownership has rapidly improved over the past decade, financial inclusion remains a major issue.

World Bank surveys indicate that those without accounts have trouble with:

  • Rural exclusion - physical bank branches and ATMs are scarce or simply too far away; this problem is tied to poorly developed physical infrastructure and public transportation.
  • High transaction costs or income thresholds - some banks impose minimum balance requirements that may price out low-income individuals; the pricing model might be a result of high operating costs for bank branches in low-density areas.
  • Cultural factors - cash is often the preferred medium of exchange for many; reliance on informal savings groups and moneylenders is also commonplace.
  • Irregular income streams - many Africans have informal jobs or gig work, which makes it difficult to meet minimum balance or usage requirements.
  • Documentation - government-issued IDs or address verification are often difficult for individuals to obtain in less populated and lower-income areas; high compliance costs associated with AML and KYC regulations often discourage banks from targeting low-income or high-risk populations.

Africans deal with barriers to banking access based on age, gender, income, location, working status, and more. Limited bank access means stifled economic growth, less entrepreneurship, lower savings for individuals (and higher vulnerability to economic shocks), and lower efficiency since more transactions are informal and cash-based. Thankfully, given Africa’s high mobile device penetration, much of its population has been able to access “mobile money” services, which have grown rapidly over the past five to ten years.

Kenya-based M-Pesa, a mobile money transfer service, is probably the poster-child for Africa’s mobile finance revolution. M-Pesa allows users to deposit, withdraw, transfer, pay for goods and services, and access credit and savings all on their mobile device. M-Pesa’s primary innovation was creating a branchless company using a decentralized network of agents and retail outlets (that handle cash deposits) to provide microfinance services. One can see how new crypto rails and applications might be the perfect fit for such a set of circumstances, as we will detail later.

LATAM and Eastern Europe

LATAM and Eastern Europe face similar challenges, with bank account ownership rates around 74% and and 78% respectively. Most of the large increase in financial inclusion in the LATAM region has been driven by improvements in digital payments and e-commerce during Covid. Internet and banking penetration increased rapidly as small businesses incorporated digital platforms like Pix, a real-time payment system launched by Brazil’s Central Bank. Other consumer apps like MercadoPago (launched by e-commerce firm MercadoLibre) have Pix as an option for instant payments. However, they also offer other financial services like credit, insurance, investment products, and easy payments on its ecommerce arm. Much of the average user’s services are thus conducted through these financial super-apps, as opposed to typical bank accounts. Revolut, which has greatly expanded its crypto offerings in 2024, may be the equivalent super-app in Eastern Europe. It has democratized access to a range of financial services to more than 25 million users globally, with a substantial portion in Poland, Romania, and the Baltics.

Some emerging markets have largely bypassed the standard physical bank branch model, and instead rely on mobile-native apps and decentralized networks. While we noted the progress these regions have made in the past decade with standard fintech companies, the penetration of crypto apps and rails has been occurring simultaneously. To understand where the crypto-based growth has come from, we need to dig into the history and growth of one of the oldest L1s.

USDT on Tron: A Case Study in Distribution and First-Mover Advantage

History and EM Ties

The Tron network initially gained traction by offering high throughput and low transaction fees, setting itself apart from Ethereum, which began to struggle with high gas costs and network congestion. Tron began issuing USDT natively after a partnership with Tether in early 2019. Binance began supporting USDT on Tron in September 2019 with a 16% APR during a promotional period. They also quietly implemented free withdrawals and internal transfers, which was a huge competitive edge over expensive ERC20 transfers; this would cement a sticky behavior around stablecoin transfers for many global users on Binance. From October to December 2019, the supply of USDT on Tron skyrocketed from around $100 million to almost $1 billion, representing around 30% of USDT supply at the time. Tron's strategic partnership with Binance and subsidizing of this user behavior is probably one of the most under-rated moves in the nascent stablecoin ecosystem.

Given Binance’s large presence in Kenya, Nigeria, Argentina, (formerly) Russia, Ukraine, and other emerging markets, it’s no surprise that this move may have resulted in a huge first-mover advantage for USDT on Tron. The head of Tether has also mentioned USDT’s reach and influence in EMs. Anecdotally, interviews with EM merchants indicate that most of their customers choose to transact with USDT on Tron because they were accustomed to or trust it over alternatives. Merchants obviously want to accept whichever payment is most popular among their customers, so there is an entrenchment of past behaviors. Users are less familiar with newer L2s even though fees might be substantially cheaper. And as long as the network gets the job done more cheaply than traditional avenues, users do not care much about debates over centralization.

Growth

As stablecoin market capitalization continues to hit new highs, it’s notable that for multiple years the majority of USDT’s $135 billion in supply was held on Tron. This ~$60 billion in USDT on Tron was only recently surpassed by USDT on Ethereum, driven by an almost $15 billion increase in supply in this past month. It’s unclear what has driven the recent surge on Ethereum, but Tron’s historical lead has been strong.

According to Artemis, monthly transfer volumes on Tron have also grown from around $350 billion last year to more than $500 billion this November. Tron’s share of monthly transfer volume across chains has been fairly steady, while Solana and Base seem to be taking some transfer volume that used to occur on Ethereum mainnet. As Castle Island noted in their research, the steady growth indicates that a lot of this activity is likely linked to non-speculative and non-trading activity. This becomes more apparent when looking more closely at onchain activity.

User Behavior

While the initial push from Binance funneled its global user base into transacting with USDT on a centralized exchange, user behavior evolved into more peer-to-peer transactions. Artemis shows that more than 90% of the $507 billion transfer volume for USDT on Tron was between externally owned accounts (p2p). Meanwhile, a much lower percentage of stablecoin transfers on Ethereum, Base, and Solana were considered p2p.

According to a cohort analysis by CryptoQuant, small USDT holders (less than $1,000 per wallet) made up almost 30% of total stablecoin transactions on Tron. This was the largest cohort by number of transactions across wallets, indicating a high degree of retail usage. Chainalysis data around when USDT transfers usually occur also coincides with peak business hours in emerging markets. All of the above seems to indicate that much of the expanding stablecoin activity on Tron is everyday consumers using USDT for payments on a regular basis.

Translation to Fees and Price

The growth of USDT on Tron has certainly contributed to Tron’s fee growth over the last year. Tron’s fees have even outpaced Ethereum (which still dominates in DeFi activity) and Solana (which has generated huge fees from more speculative trading activity) this year. While using a different architecture from most other L1s, Tron has network resources called energy and bandwidth that are consumed through transactions like stablecoin transfers. These costs are paid in TRX, which creates a demand sink for the token; simultaneously, a portion of those fees are burned over time depending on the level of network activity.

The market has at least partially rewarded this improvement in fundamentals. TRX has outperformed ETH, BNB, TON, and AVAX from prices a year ago. TRX was also one of the only L1s to break its 2021 high a few months ago (and move substantially above it since). While underappreciated by allocators in relation to SOL, TRX is perhaps one of the few liquid, fully-diluted tokens one can allocate to express bullishness on the growth of stablecoins.

Much of stablecoin transfer volumes and activity will continue to take place through Tron, but there are new players coming to market that may funnel more activity elsewhere as well.

The Emergent Stablecoin and Payment Players

Yellow Card - Seamless Stablecoin Swaps for Africa

While Tron was pushing its USDT adoption efforts in 2019, Yellow Card was launched as a Bitcoin exchange in Nigeria. The founders of Yellow Card, Chris Maurice and Justin Poiroux, saw the need for cheaper means for transferring funds to and within emerging markets when an acquaintance told them they spent $90 to send a remittance to family in Nigeria.

What started as a simple way to exchange or send Bitcoin across borders has now turned into a stablecoin behemoth on the African continent. Yellow Card is now available across 20 countries in Africa, allowing for seamless swapping between local currencies and stablecoins like USDT, USDC, and PYUSD. This has brought huge cost savings for the average remittance-sender, as using traditional service providers like MoneyGram or Western Union can incur substantial fees. Yellow Card has intelligently integrated with the mobile money operators we mentioned earlier for smoother onboarding. Since their beginnings in Africa in 2019, they’ve grown to more than 1.7 million retail users.

Yellow Card has grown rapidly and recently reached almost $90 million in cumulative funding as it expands its array of services. However, over this time, Maurice began to encounter some of the same problems African commercial banks ran into in the past: namely the large expense of regulatory compliance, KYC checks, and other screenings. Users themselves have been complaining in app store reviews about the verification process and delays in using their accounts. Given that these retail accounts are lower margin, Yellow Card has shifted its focus towards supporting businesses with cash management and stablecoin APIs for on/off-ramping. The argument for moving “away from the masses” is that for a largely informal economy driven by gig work, small businesses and individuals are often one and the same. It’s possible that the societal-level economic improvements occur not with p2p payment solutions - which are available in other forms - but rather giving businesses that import essential goods the ability to acquire and sell those goods more cheaply.

And this is not to say Yellow Card is forgetting about the little guy. In fact, they recently made stablecoin transfers free across certain stablecoins on Polygon, Solana, Celo, and Base. Notably, USDT on Tron and Ethereum still have small transfer fees around $1.50. While Yellow Card does not quite have the distribution that Binance had in 2019, it will be interesting to see if this similar subsidization might shift user behavior towards or away from certain networks.

Bitso - LATAM’s Exchange Giant

Founded in 2014 and headquartered in Mexico City, Bitso has rapidly ascended to become one of Latin America’s leading cryptocurrency exchanges. Serving more than eight million users across countries such as Mexico, Argentina, Brazil, and Colombia, Bitso has positioned itself as a crucial platform in the region’s fintech ecosystem. While the exchange’s volume profile is very different from Yellow Card’s (which is 90%+ stablecoin-driven), much of the volume is still driven by stablecoin-local currency pairs. It remains a central hub for stablecoin transfers and swaps in the LATAM region.

The company was quite early in developing its focus on remittances, developing “Bitso Shift,” a cross-border payment system between Mexico and the US, in 2021. This move was particularly important for allowing small-to-medium enterprises in Mexico who sell into the US to be able to process payments properly. Bitso developed its own instant transfer app that is integrated with the SPEI (Mexico’s interbank transfer system) for easy deposits and transfers. The company noted it recently processed around 10% of total US-Mexico remittances, which has averaged around $65 billion in volumes per year.

While Bitso Shift was launched in partnership with Circle in 2021, it is notable that the top volume pairs on the exchange are still USDT, not USDC or new players like PYUSD. As CIV detailed in its survey results: “In cases where Tether is preferred, the primary reasons reported are its network effects, followed by user trust, liquidity, and its track record relative to other stablecoins.” As we noted in our last stablecoin piece, unseating Tether’s moat in global markets has been exceedingly difficult.

Kuna - Eastern Europe’s War-time Dollar Platform

Countries in Eastern Europe have less of an issue with bank ownership rates compared to those in Sub-Saharan Africa. The European countries that saw the greatest increase in crypto adoption (Russia, Ukraine, and Poland) have fairly high ownership rates compared to other developing nations. However, crypto rails and stablecoins are still finding a place in these markets, as dollar access and funding remain incredibly important.

While countries struggling with high inflation (Nigeria and Argentina) see the appeal of stablecoins as a store of value, countries like Ukraine rushed to the safety of stablecoins to escape war-driven local currency volatility. Kuna was founded in 2015 in Kyiv, and is now one of the top crypto exchanges in Eastern Europe. Kuna gained a lot of attention at the beginning of the conflict between Russia and Ukraine in February 2022, as it provided the framework for Ukraine’s crypto donations from abroad. Ukraine’s initial effort at crowdfunding accepted BTC, ETH, and, of course, USDT on Tron. Ukrainians began paying a 10% premium for USDT as they swapped out of their native currency on Kuna. The premium continues to linger around 5-7%, highlighting continued demand for dollars that cannot be easily accessed elsewhere.

Since 2022, Kuna has also expanded its product offerings. It is taking a similar approach to Yellow Card in offering payment APIs that allow small businesses to accept crypto. KUNA Pay allows for crypto bank account creation, invoicing, mass payouts for employees, and other tools. This product has been a particular boon to freelancers who have global clients and need seamless cross-border payments.

Looking Forward

Stablecoins are fundamentally transforming the financial landscapes of emerging markets by providing accessible, efficient, and reliable alternatives to traditional banking systems. Unlike the institutional-driven adoption seen in Western economies, emerging markets such as Sub-Saharan Africa, Latin America, and Eastern Europe are experiencing grassroots growth fueled by retail users engaging in small transfers, remittances, peer-to-peer payments, and value storage.

The lessons from the proliferation of USDT on Tron tell us that user behavior is awfully sticky and can be driven by large points of distribution to the largest number of users. In the past, these points were - and to some degree still are - centralized exchanges. But as we have detailed here, the lines between CeFi, DeFi, and the emerging “PayFi” verticals are blurring. CEXs are moving into payments, payment companies are bolstering their stablecoin capabilities, and traditional “Fintech” is melding with crypto rails. It’s likely that the next set of sticky user behaviors in the stablecoin space will be driven by these consumer super-apps as they continue to evolve and lap their traditional banking counterparts. Both retail users and small businesses have much to gain from the success of this burgeoning sector.
